The purpose of a will being the bestowal of the universal successim, the institution of the heir or heirs was regarded as of more importance than any other part—as in fact the only part which was in every case indispensable, ‘ quia testamenta vim ex institutione heredis accipiunt, ob id velut caput et fundamentum intellegitur totius testamenti heredis in- stitutio’ Gaius ii. 229: cf. Tit. 20. 34 inf. Hence, under the old law, no disposition could precede it in the will except exheredations (e. g. legacy or manumission); and the Sabinians even held that the appointment of a testamentary guardian ante heredis institutionem was void (Gaius ii. 230-1). This was all changed by Justinian, Tit. 20. 34 int„ Bk. i. 14. 3 supin, Cod. 6. 23· 24.
